                The World of Commodore-Amiga '93, Take 1
                              by @{" Nick Cook " link nick }

Apparently nobody told the folks crowding Pasadena's World of Commodore
Amiga that the Amiga is precariously perched at the edge of the extinction
abyss. The vendor demonstration areas were standing room only and
navigating the floor required more than a few "excuse me...excuse
me..excuse me..."s by early afternoon. The Amiga's current market position
was also evident, with most of the 40 plus exhibitors displaying graphics,
video, or multimedia wares.

In Commodore's spacious booth, curious onlookers four or five deep
clustered around the three displayed CD^32s. "Jurassic Park", featuring
clips from the film, ran on one machine, a football simulation, including
digitized TV announcers, played on a second CD^32, while an arcade
platform game bounced around on the third. While the quality of the clips
won't be mistaken for "real" video, they're better than what's currently
on game machines. Commodore also displayed the complete Amiga line,
including the yet-to-be-released 4000 tower.

Soft-Logik Publishing performed hourly demonstrations on its coming DTP
powerhouse, PageStream 3.0. Comparison to programs available on the Amiga
and other platforms, spelled out in small print on a four page flyer,
can't be reviewed here, but some features jumped out at me. Full color bit
map pictures are now supported, and text can "flow" around irregularly
shaped graphics. The graphics and text import features perform double
duty: they translate and export in other formats. For example, import a
TIFF graphic, export it as an IFF; import WordPerfect, export as Final
Copy. PageStream hosts many features which may not be exactly earth
shaking, but will save a heck of a lot of time. These include a bunch of
automatic functions: paragraph bullets, drop caps, backup, hypenation and
kerning. Creating AREXX macros couldn't be simplier: turn on "Record",
perform whatever keystrokes/actions desired, then turn off "Record".
Viola! Instant AREXX script! You can even edit it. Like the famous battery
bunny, PageStream's features go on and on and on... Shipping date is
projected to be no later than mid November.

The number of graphic boards available for the Amiga are increasing,
giving owners of A2000s and A3000s a method to upgraded their systems
without having to buy new machines. The Retina board, a 24 bit display
board which includes Workbench emulation, an optional 1084 monitor
adapter, and AGA emulation, was on display at the MacroSystems US booth.
Two new boards have entered the fray. The Piccolo board from DKB offers
True 16 and 24 bit modes, fully programmable resolutions from 320X200 to
1280 X 1024, double buffering, an optional video module and a single
monitor system with automatic monitor switching, among other things.
Expert Services had Picasso II, billed as the first retargetable graphics
board for the Amiga. The Picasso does not require chip RAM, emulates AGA
chip sets and Workbench, and contains its own on-board blitter. 24 bit
graphics are available in resolutions up to 800 x 768, and the board
supports 256 color Intuition screens up to 1280 x 1024. Centaur
Development's demonstrations of OpalVision pulled in the crowds at its
large booth situated by the shows entrance. The much talked about, but
delayed, Video Modules for OpalVision were previewed in seminars.


Scala presented seemingly continuous (at least the same guy was talking
every time I walked by!) demonstrations of their MM300 multimedia creation
program. This program allows the user to resize freely imported brushes,
and includes an "optimize" function that automatically calculates the best
palette for a page after several different brushes, pictures and text
colors have been used on that page. MM300 offers new wipes, including the
intrigingly named "Nuclear". Just when you thought the Cold War was over.
Text now can "crawl" from the screen without dragging the background with
it. Sound samples load directly from the hard disk, limited sample size to
disk space, not RAM. Although not displayed at the show, Scala's
InfoChannel IC500 will "broadcast" presentations across multiple screens,
and will let these be updated without interrupting playback.

VideoStage Pro, from Oxxi, creates presentations to run on kiosks, for use
in training, or even for video catalogs. Along with the expected funtions,
VideoStage permits animation of individual characters, lines of text or
blocks of text using any Amiga fonts, including compugraphic fonts. An
interesting feature is the "Hot Test". This checks for illegal video
colors that would bleed in NTSC or PAL, then allows the user to adjust the
color levels. VideoStage Pro includes remote control, not only through
Arexx, but also via modems and networks. The program checks for time and
date changes, and then loads new file versions automatically. Great way
for easy updates.

Creative Computers and Century Computer Systems did brisk business selling
all manner of Amiga hardware and software. Public domain libraries stocked
disks and videotapes. Along with its line of disk collections, Premier
Software's booth displayed a special "collectible" Amiga: a 2000 signed by
Jay Miner! DevWare featured its line of instructional video tapes and low-
cost, high featured software. Several Amigas demonstrated titles including
the music creator "OctaMED Professional", an easy to learn morphing and
image warping application called "Cocoon", and the authoring program
"Helm". NorthWest Public Domain offered choices from its over 3000 disk
library, as well as its exclusive double CDTV set of British public domain
titles.

Jim Drew and his Emplant consistently drew a crowd around the Utilities
Unlimited booth. The Amiga/Mac emulation ran side by side to a regular Mac
to allow for direct comparisons. The show even presented hardware to allow
the Amiga to emulate an Amiga! Warm and Fuzzy Logic, Inc. (bonus points
for the best company name) introduced "LightRave", a hardware Toaster
emulator which allows NewTek's Lightwave 3.D to run on a Toaster-less
Amiga. Renderings can be output to 24 bit cards, Amiga and Amiga AGA
displays. LightRave can be networked with ParNet or Ethernet. A newcomer
to the show from the PC and Mac world was Fargo Electronics. They showed
off the Primera, an under $1000 (well, OK, $995) thermal transfer color
printer which can be upgraded into an "advanced dye-sublimation" color
printer. I'm sure somebody out there understands what the heck that is.
All I can say is the Primera sure printed out purty pictures!

Sunrize Industries demonstrated version 3 of its Studio 16 board. This
hummer includes complete 8 track stereo, 16-bit audio editing using a
graphic interface time cue list. You can make non-linear sound edits and
adjust fades and cross-fades by using your mouse. A definite step up from
cueing audio tape!

GVP's booth featured Warner Brothers animator Rusty Mills, who explained
how GVP's ImageFX is used in the creation of the new cartoon show
"Animanics". He stated that the Amiga was somewhat easier to use than the
Mac, since the Amiga's output is RGB and the output can be networked
straight to the SGI-controlled film recorder. The Mac output has to go
through the additional step of translated its output from PIC format to
RGB. An Animanics cartoon was  screened. It was hilarious; the style
managed to recapture the off-the-wall humor of those great 1930s and 1940s
Looney Tunes. Suffice to say that the plot managed to roll Kirk Douglas,
Steven Spielberg, the Sistine Chapel, and ET into one deranged bundle.

Mashing animations down to a more manageable size was tackled by Heifner
Communications, Inc. They showed off their automated JPEG program
"Pegger". The program runs in the background and can compress 30 plus high
resolution video frames on a single floppy. Heifner also displayed their
Toaster Cozy which now operates on the A4000.

Animation software from Axiom (Pixel3D), and Terra Nova Development (Magic
Lantern) was on view. Terra Nova also stopped traffic with "The Labyrinth
of Time", a CD-ROM game (running here on a CDTV) which features over 280
rooms, a 30 minute soundtrack and over 180MB of ray-traced images.

The print media was in attendance. Booths sold subscriptions to Amiga
World, Desktop Video, Amazing Amiga, and Video Toaster User. Merrill
Callaway autographed copies of his "Arexx Cookbook". International
Networking Corporation displayed its range of British imported Amiga help
books.

Phew! And there was more! I left the World of Commodore Amiga, tired, with
a lighter wallet and a bag of goodies including brand new Picasso II
board. I don't want to be Candide, and proclaim "this is the best of all
possible worlds." But when I got home, I patted my trusty A3000. There
still a lot of life in the old girl yet.


