                The World of Commodore-Amiga '93 - Take 2
                            by @{" Matt Davidian " link matt }

If anyone tells you that the Amiga is dying, then they haven't been to a
World of Commodore show recently.  Even with Commodore's recent financial
problems, the level of enthusiam at the World of Commodore in Pasadena was
comparable to a year ago.

A year ago, we had the introduction of the exciting A4000 and the AGA
graphics chips. This year, after reporting losses, Commodore introduced
the Amiga CD32; possibly less exciting in the minds of Amiga users, since
it's not a "power system".  But after seeing it and the enormous potential
it holds, I can't help but wonder if this is the key to regenerating a
beleaguered Commodore--if Commodore pumps CD32 for all it's worth.

On the third party front, new products were everywhere.  Graphics boards
were well represented with companies like Digital Micronics,
MacroSystemUS, Expert Services, GVP, and Centaur Development showing the
latest and greatest graphics add ons.  Despite Commodore's lack of an RTG
standard, third party companies have forged ahead with varying solutions
to get Amiga software to work on their boards.

Soft-Logik touted the advantages of PageSetter 3 over XPress 3.2 and
PageMaker 5.0, claiming that ProPage 4.1 wasn't even in the running.
Version 2.0 of TypeSmith was also announced.  GVP promoted its second
generation A1200 accelerator, a new graphics board, and its image
processing software ImageFX.  Scala MM300 has a host of new features to
enhance multimedia presentations (and it was great to see Scala actually
being used during the Commodore seminars (as it was last year)).  Centaur
Development showed an impressive demo tape accompanied by a techno
soundtrack for the new features of the upcoming OpalVision Video Modules.

KEYNOTE ADRESS/MPEG SEMINAR

A more somber mood was reflected in the Keynote Address.  Last year, we
got an exciting peek into the Amiga's future from Lew Eggebrecht--this
year, Jim Dionne began the Keynote Address, explaining what has happened
at Commodore in the last 12 months, what restructuring steps have been
taken, and what the product plans for the rest of 1993 are.

Dionne drew some laughs when he started out by misspeaking, saying
Commodore has had a rough past 12 years (instead of months).  The
increasingly competitive computer market has led to declining profit
margins.  80% of Commodore's sales are in Europe, where there's been an
"economic slowdown".  This, combined with a strong U.S. dollar, has pushed
Commodore's total sales figure down.  In addition, inventory write downs
have taken their toll.  On the bright side, Dionne said that Commodore has
taken its "bad medicine" and has a clean slate beginning its new fiscal
year.

The MPEG video cartridge add-on was big news.  Expected in November, this
add on will play back VideoCD disks with 74 minutes of video.  One of the
five CD32 units in the Commodore booth was equipped with a prototype, and
played music videos from a CD.  (The three videos were Bon Jovi's "Blaze
of Glory", Enya's "Caribbean Blue", and Seal's "Killer")

I was very surprised by the quality of the VideoCD.  Although the MPEG
compression routine discards information and plays back at a resolution of
352x240, the videos were easily as good or better than VHS tapes. The
VideoCDs don't have tracking problems, they don't wear out, and the audio
is as good as a regular CD.

The MPEG module does virtually all the work in playing the VideoCD disks.
All the 68EC020 must do is read data from the CD and send it to the audio
and video chips on the MPEG cartridge.  This takes up about 30% of the
processor's time, leaving a lot of potential.  The AGA chips are not used
to generate the video, the cartridge takes care of this.  However, AGA
graphics can be genlocked over the MPEG video.  This was used to a limited
extent by the current prototype player software, which used Amiga graphics
to display the song title, artist, time remaining and time played.
Needless to say, there is quite a bit of potential that can be put to use.

The prototype software itself has some glitches, which is to be expected.
There were apparently a few video glitches which I didn't notice, but were
explained as problems with the driver software. Also, the prototype player
only plays the videos, and does not yet allow for fast forward/rewind,
pausing, etc.  The interface is modeled after the CDTV's for playing
regular CD's, but that is likely to change and become more textual in
nature.  This is because the VideoCD can store the artist and titles, and
it may be better to display these than simply allowing the user to pick a
track number. The controller does have all the audio/VideoCD controls
labeled on it, so you don't have to have your TV/monitor on to control it,
although the CD32 itself has no LEDs or other indicators like a regular CD
player.

In both the Keynote Address and the MPEG seminar, it was indicated that
Commodore intends to be competitive in price with other CD platforms (3DO
and CD-I) for the VideoCD add on.  Although a firm price was not given, it
is expected to be $250 or less.  Commodore should have an advantage over
CD-I and 3DO for the VideoCD attachment, in that the Amiga graphics
systems is genlock ready.

It was stressed that the VideoCD format (which is about 3 months old) is
an industry standard, and many big name companies (Sony, Paramount, Warner
Bros., etc.) are interested in providing VideoCD disks.  The fact that
other companies besides Commodore will have VideoCD players strengthens
the potential of it becoming widespread. Commodore will have to
differentiate CD32 from the others to show the advantages of CD32.

The expansion bus (which the MPEG cartridge plugs into) provides full
processor, video, and audio connections.  CPU accelerators are possible
using this bus.

PRODUCT REPORTS

Jim Drew talked up the advantages of an Amiga with Emplant over the
Macintosh--in effect a better Macintosh than Macintosh to borrow a phrase
from IBM.  (All the while, I was cringing as he flexed an Emplant board
back and forth, expecting it to snap any minute.) Emplant now supports the
use of the Retina graphics board, allowing a 24 bit Macintosh display on
the Amiga.  Support for other video boards is currently in progress.  The
A3000 will run twice as fast as a Macintosh IIx.  Drew indicated that for
IBM compatible emulation, Intel 80x86 binaries will actually be translated
into 680x0 code, explaining how Emplant will deliver promised 386/486
emulation without the addition of a processor to the Emplant board.

SunRize industries demonstrated their Studio 16 hardware/software
combination.  Although there were a few minor technical glitches the
software is quite impressive in its ease of use.  Samples can be arranged
at will along 8 tracks and play in 16-bit CD quality.  They can be grouped
together if you need to keep them together (for instance, two samples each
going to separate left and right channels).  Volume adjustment, fade in
and fade out are all point and click operations.  They also showed how
incoming SMPTE time-code can be used to trigger the playing of samples.  A
movie trailer ("Expert Weapon") that was actually done with Studio 16 was
shown, with the video supplying the SMPTE time-code and the Studio 16
providing the audio in sync with the video.

The Picasso II graphics board is boasting the first true retargetable
graphics emulator for the Amiga.  Basically it allows any application that
uses the ASL screen mode requester to select a Picasso screen mode.  The
system does not use chip RAM; the currently displayed screen is kept in
the boards memory, and other screens can be stored in fast RAM. When a new
screen is switched to the front, it is quickly copied out of fast RAM into
the Picasso II's memory.  Picasso II supports the following resolutions:

  640 x  480, 2-256 colors
  800 x  600, 2-256 colors
 1024 x  768, 2-256 colors
 1120 x  832, 2-256 colors
 1152 x  900, 2-256 colors
 1280 x 1024, 2-256 colors

In addition, 24 bit graphics are supported in 640 x 480 and 800 x 600
resolutions, and a 64K colors in resolutions 1024 x 768 and above. The
Picasso II comes in both 1Mb and 2Mb versions, the 2Mb version being
necessary for the highest resolutions.

A different approach has been taken by GVP for its EGS-28/24 Spectrum.
The Spectrum is capable of using the Enhanced Graphics System device
library, which means that software has to be rewritten for it.  On the
plus side, software rewritten to the EGS library will work on any EGS
compatible board, and the function calls for the EGS library are as close
as possible to the Amiga's own graphics calls, which make porting
relatively simple.  The Spectrum also supports multiple boards and
monitors on the same computer, which can be very useful when you need to
see several things at once.  The Spectrum can also pass through the
Amiga's own display, which means you don't need a separate monitor for
both displays.

The Spectrum comes with 2Mb of display memory.  It uses a Cirrus Logic
video controller/processor which has a blitter.  A Workbench driver allows
non-EGS software that runs on the Workbench screen to be displayed by the
Spectrum.  The board will autosense whether it is in a Zorro II or Zorro
III machine, and has a "Zorro II force" option for Amigas that have
problems with 32-bit DMA on the Zorro III bus. In a Zorro II machine the
bus bandwidth is 3.5Mb/sec; in a Zorro III machine the bandwidth is
12Mb/sec.  The native EGS software list was quite short: EGS-Paint,
Rainbow Painter, an MPEG player still in development, and a Connect Four
game.

Like the Picasso II, the Spectrum supports 24 bit graphics in resolutions
up to 800 x 600, and 8 bit graphics up to 1280 x 1024. The Spectrum can go
up to 1600 x 1280 with 4 bits (16 colors).

One pleasant surprise was the Primera color printer from Fargo
Electronics.  What's most surprising is that they have been focusing on
the IBM PC compatible and Macintosh markets, and have recently added Amiga
support--to the point of writing their own Amiga printer driver, bundling
it with the printer, and offering it free (presumably for users who may
have already have access to a Primera, and would like to use the Amiga
with it).  They are so new to the Amiga market that the sample printouts
were done on Windows and Macintosh computers, although they did have an
Amiga running AdPro to demonstrate the printer.

The printer itself uses wax thermal transfer technology, and outputs at a
resolution of 203x203 dots per inch.  The price is $995 (the show special
price was about $750) and an optional $250 dye sublimation kit allows the
printer to produce exceptional graphics that knocked many people's socks
off.  If I looked very closely, I could see a few jagged edges, betraying
the printers 203 dpi resolution, but this is about the closest you can get
to near photographic quality at this price.

To achieve the low price point, some things have been sacrificed. The
Primera is a "dumb printer"; without an internal processor, only 32Kb of
RAM, and one internal font.  The printer is also slower than more
expensive color thermal printers, printing one page in two and a half
minutes.  The 203 dpi resolution also helped to cut costs; a 300 dpi
printer would have cost $200 to $300 more.

The Primera is especially targeted at presentation graphics because it is
more economical than ink jet printers when there is a high percentage of
coverage.  Amiga owners who need to produce output where most of the page
is covered should take a serious look at the Primera.

GVP introduced the second generation of their 1200 accelerator, the Turbo+
Performance Series II.  It features a full 68030 at 50Mhz, instead of the
40Mhz 68EC030 on the A1230 Tubro+.  A 68882 math coprocessor running at
50Mhz is optional.  A battery backed up clock, an option connector, and
two SIMM sockets round out the feature list. The SIMM sockets can accept
1Mb, 4Mb or 16Mb SIMMs.  The first product for the option connector is the
A1291 SCSI module.

Axiom's WaveMaker allows the automated creation of flying 3D logos with
Lightwave.  This may be a very specialized application, but the ease with
which you can set up an animation to be rendered is incredible.  It almost
as simple as selecting the logo you want to fly onto the screen (and how
you want it fly on and off) and what "elements" you want in the
background.  The "elements" consist of streaks, stars, etc. that you may
not notice when they are there, but do notice when they are missing.  The
logo can be centered on the screen, no matter what its final orientation
is.

Wavemaker can also be used to set up several animations for Lightwave to
render all in a row for unattended rendering.  Although the beta version
demonstrated at the seminar was incomplete, this looks to be very popular
among anyone who needs to do impressive flying logos quickly.

For those who need peer-to-peer networking, Interworks ENLAN-DFS may fit
the bill.  It works over Ethernet and allows volumes, files, and printers
on other workstations to act as local devices.  Password protection on
public resources, read only access, usernames and passwords provides
levels of security for data on the network. ENLAN-DFS supports ASDG Lan
ROVER, Commodore 2065, Ameristar, and Hydra interfaces for the 2000, 3000,
and 4000, and Interworks new PCMCIA Ethernet card.

The I-Card is Interwork's new PCMCIA Ethernet interface for the A1200 and
A600.  It is compatible with Commodore's SANA-II standard, and has 10BaseT
and 10Base2 connectors.  At $299 for the I-Card, and $349 for a 5-node
license of ENLAN-DFS, this may not be solution for the casual home user
who needs to hook up two machines. In a situation where there are several
Amigas of mixed types and peripherals need to be shared among them,
ENLAN-DFS is worth looking into.

Lightwave users might also want to take a look at Interworks Toaster-Net
software, which provides the capabilities of setting up a render-farm.
Its features include the ability to render a sequence of Lightwave
scenes, render selective frames, delegate rendering across the network,
automate moving complete scenes between systems, and monitor the status of
the render-farm.  Toaster-Net requires Toaster 3.0 software, and
Interworks recommends using ENLAN-DFS with it to take full advantage of
its capabilities.  Toaster-Net is also priced at $349 per 5-nodes.



