                The World of Commodore-Amiga '93 - Take 3
                              by @{" Eric Penn " link eric }

Anyone who has ever taken a transistor radio onto an airplane knows that
you can really get a "feel" for a region simply by listening to the radio
stations in that area.  Likewise, during a 7 hour drive halfway across a
state, one can get feel for the prevelant attitudes there.  And having
just made the same trip exactly a year previous, the differences are
amazingly obvious, and the similarities shocking.

This year's west-coast WoCA show did not feature the standard-dissolving,
mind-blowing transformation of the "old" ECS Amiga into the amazing new
AGA Amiga.  Instead, the initial US introduction of the Amiga CD^32
appears to be a true phoenix, about to rise from the ashes of what was
once Commodore US.

Technically this machine is the most advanced Amiga ever.  What it lacks
in sheer processor speed, it makes up for in snazzy engineering.  The
newest addition to the Amiga "family" of custom chips, Akiko, coupled with
the AGA enhancements made last year, is sure to breathe new life into the
Amiga. Even the most adamant anti-Amiga developer will no longer have any
valid excuses to not convert the best selling games to this new machine.

Did I say "games"?  Yes, I did.  While the Amiga CD^32 is in fact a real
Amiga computer, capable of any task that any other Amiga can handle and
more, it will be marketed as a "game machine" along side the Sega Genesis
and the Nintendo SNES boxes.  And along side them, it should sell.

Wait a minute.  That word... "marketed".  For years Commodore has been
almost vehement in its ANTI-marketing stance, it has almost seemed as if
they were trying to not sell machines.  Well, brace yourself.  Things have
really changed.  In his keynote speech, Jim Dionne, President of
Commodore's U.S. Operations, acknowledged the companies poor performance
over the last year. Despite the depressing subject, Mr. Dionne presented
the image of a company that is willing to change with the times, adapt to
the current market, and ready to take the initiative needed to regain
market share.  In an unplanned slip of the tongue during his opening
remarks he said "We have had a very tough twelve years... er... months."
The crowd responded with a chuckle, which set the stage for the
encouraging news he presented. Commodore -is- in the process of
rebuilding.  Regardless of what some doomsayers may lead you to believe,
Commodore US has a very good idea of where they are, and where they are
going.  And from the looks of things, they even know how to get there.

On the subject of advertising, one of the demonstrations running on the
CD^32 machines on the floor would make an incredible 15-second television
advertisement.  The screen fades in from black to a typical Sega-esque
game. A tiny player sprite runs from screen right to screen left, being
pursued by a much larger dinosaur sprite.  A male voiceover says, "Is this
your idea of playing games?"  The dinosaur sprite reaches mid- screen.  It
pauses.  The voiceover asks, "Or is THIS!?" as the dinosaur sprite doubles
in size, morphing into a 256-color, texture mapped, photo-realistic,
anamatronic beast.  It turns its head to look out the screen at the
viewer, opens its many toothed maw and ROARS!  Fade to black.  A shiver
of excitement ran down my spine as I imagined the closing voiceover, "The
new Amiga CD^32, the world's first 32-bit game machine.  Coming soon to a
store near you."  None of the Commodore employees would comment on this
supposition.

However, one of the staff on hand did describe the -actual- television
commercial which is currently in production and will be running very soon
in Europe.  What his description was lacking in detail, it more than made
up for in content.  The scene is a dank dungeon.  Two scientific looking
individuals clad in white lab coats hover over a CD^32.  One asks,
"32-bit, you say?"  The other replies, "Yes, but don't touch it!  It's
part of an experiment!"  He then opens a very LARGE door and in walks a 12
foot tall robot: THE ULTIMATE GAME PLAYER.  The robot picks up the
controller and begins to play.  Several one-second shots of a variety of
games will then be shown, followed by the robot exploding in a shower of
sparks!  The two scientists look at each other and proclaims the
superiority of the CD^32 by virtue of its 32-bit design.

If the show had included nothing else besides the Commodore keynote
speeches and the five CD^32 machines displayed on the show floor, it would
have been worth attending.  Instead, a bevy of 24-bit display cards
peppered the show floor.  Last year's WoCA show focused on Video
Production and morphing software, this year was the year of the 24-bit
display card. Firecracker, OpalVision, Picasso II, Piccolo, EGS-28/24
Spectrum, Retina, Video Toaster; old, and new, there has never before been
such an array of display options available to the Amiga user.

Utilities Unlimited was running the amazing Emplant on three different
Amiga models, along side a real Macintosh II.  Several show-goers
approached with "real" Macintosh disks to try out on Emplant.  Nearly all
worked fine, without even so much as a burp from Emplant.  The solitary
exception was a disk which upon insertion into the Macintosh was
discovered to be badly damaged, and barely usable even on its native
platform.  Emulation does have its limits and apparently this test had
exceeded them.  Overall, not bad performance from a product which was
publicly discounted in many forums at its inception.  Jim Drew, president
and founder of Utilities Unlimited, mentioned that he should have the IBM
'386/'486 emulation module ready for release soon.  This is a product to
watch!

And on the other side of the show floor, two young programmers from
Richmond, VA set up shop.  The product they were hawking was a tiny
matchbox-sized box that plugs into the serial port of any Amiga and allows
it to run NewTek's LightWave 3-D modeling software, without a Video
Toaster!  Anyone who has ever wanted the ease of use and speed of
LightWave 3-D renderings, now can have it.  In the booth, an A1200 running
LightWave 3-D version 3.0 (obviously not equipped with a Video Toaster,
which requires a video slot) pumped out a rendering of a Jolt Cola can on
request.  How long will this product last?  Only time will tell.
LightWave 3-D is not included in the package (although LightWave 3-D
version 3.0 "upgrades" are available from many mail-order vendors for
about $699), so it may be difficult for NewTek to contest the legality of
the product.  Even for a user who is not "into" video production, this is
an exciting product.

A year later, and while some things are very different, some things are
very much the same.  Commodore management seems to finally found the
direction they want to move in, and have made the adjustments needed to
accomplish those goals.  Third parties continue to crank out amazing
products, and the Amiga line continues to expand at a furious and
exhilarating pace.  I can hardly wait for next year's show!


