                           The Eggebrecht Tapes

@{" Lew Eggebrecht " system "$viewer lew"} - formerly of IBM, currently Vice-President of Engineering
for Commodore Business Machines - always gives a good speech.  He has a
firm grasp on the "lore" of the Amiga, and definite ideas about its
future.  And he's a man who makes things happen.  Within the space of a
year, he oversaw the release of the Amiga 4000, 1200, CD32, and shortly
the 4000T.  And when he speaks, everyone listens.  Lew delivers his
remarks with a candor uncharacteristic of most industry representatives.

However, most Amigans never get a chance to hear him speak, and read only
bits and pieces of what he's said.  Because of that, ViewPort is proud to
present most of Lew's remarks from the 1993 World of Commodore-Amiga show
in Pasadena.  The text was transcribed from a tape recording of the
keynote speech, and has been lightly edited for readability.

"The Amiga CD32 is a project that was started shortly after we actually
started the 1200, even though it actually came out after the 1200 and
after the 4000. This was an interesting project from the standpoint that
it's probably the first time that we went to the developers and end users
and we really tried to find out what they wanted with respect to
development environment and respect to the product specifications.  And
this is unique in the fact that we ... actually talked to a number of
major game developers, and they actually assisted us in developing the
specifications of this product.

It's not just engineering standing back in a corner and doing whatever
they want.  We actually listened to the developers, and quite frankly, we
got all kinds of input and it really helped us a lot in the definition of
the product.

It is, we believe, the world's first 32-bit game console. Although it's
much more than a game console, as you will discover, we are primarily
focusing on the game environment.

We like to think of it as a follow-on to the CDTV.  In fact, it plays many
of the CDTV titles.  We learned a lot from CDTV, both from a technology
standpoint and from a marketing standpoint.

We learned that the price point of CDTV was much too high for consumer
environments, we learned that we needed more performance, and we learned
that people really wanted entertainment on these kinds of products.
Education type titles, reference material titles - they're all really
nice, but people really like to play games.  And so we first decided that
this was our major target in this product, to understand how we could play
exceptional games, and "oh, by the way, it still is an interactive
multimedia platform, and it plays most of the old CDTV titles and a lot of
new titles.

We were in a position, now that we had proven the viability of the AGA
chipset in the 1200 and the 4000, we began to understand that this
technology had to go into a CDTV-like product.  And so the AGA chipset was
proven functional and very very cost-effective and high performance, and
it was our natural choice for this kind of product.

So the same capabilities that you find in our 4000s and our 1200s, with
respect to video capabilities, exist fully in the CD games system.

We chose to upgrade the processor to the same processor that's used in the
1200, using the 68000 EC020 running at 14 MHz.  This gives us
approximately a 4 MIP capability in the machine, several times the
performance of the old machine, and some of our competitors, which are
still 68000-based - again, several times the performance.

One of the major concerns was how much memory should be in a games system.
Obviously, all the software people said "8 megabytes is just fine, it will
be easy to write code for."  And then we told them the price, and they
said "Maybe not!"  So we did - and this was a major point of discussion;
there are significant costs associated with the memory, and it ends up
representing a very significant percentage of the cost of the system, so
there are a lot of hard decisions - we chose the 2 megabyte model, because
it was compatible with the 1200, and we knew that we could do good games
in that model.


There is 1 megabyte of ROM in the system.  This contains AmigaDOS, it
contains an enhanced version of AmigaDOS - by the way, this enhanced
version will also shortly be available on the other products.  Obviously,
we needed to add the CD file system support, we made a number of
enhancements to support the game controller, and we added a number of
other features that allowed the operating system to be controlled, and
actually even shut down in some cases in a graceful manner, allowing the
developer to have full access to the bandwidth of the system.  This is a
little different approach than some of our competitors have taken, and we
believe we have the best of both worlds, we have a full-blown AmigaDOS
operating system in the game machine, and yet we allow the developer to
control what features and how he uses that operating system.

We also have 1 Kbyte of non-volatile memory that allows high scores - as a
matter of fact, you can see a little demo of how that works if you go down
to the floor.  We also designed our own custom CD-ROM drive.  One of the
key things that allows us to achieve the price point of $399, it is very
very cost effective CD-ROM drive technology.

We learned a lot from the activity that we had with the CDTV, and our
experience there, and as a result, combining a Sony mechanism with our own
custom design and our own microcode, we achieved an outstanding
performance at extremely low cost.  The drive does support a 2x speed
mode, and also supports multisession capability.  This allows us to
eventually support, for example, Kodak PhotoCD, which requires
multisession capability.

The system supports the standard Amiga audio, 4-voice stereo capability.
It also naturally supports the CD 16-bit capability.  So audio can be
selected either as generated from Amiga or directly from the CD drive.

Of course, we support a stereo line out capability - there's a connector
at the back.  We have a headset port, which also has a volume control,
although the headset itself is not shipped with the machine; any standard
unit that you purchase - at Radio Shack, for example - will operate.

From a video standpoint, we support, from an output capability, RF output
- with an RF modulator built in to the unit; there's no external device
required. That comes standard with the unit.  We support the composite
video output, and we also support an S-video output for the new TVs.  If
you've ever tried the S-Video port, it makes a very significant
improvement in the video quality, allowing the full video capability of
the machine to be demonstrated.

And of course, it has the capabilities of the AGA chipset - 256 colors out
of a palette of 16 million, or - using the HAME (HAM8) mode - in excess of
256 thousand colors simultaneously on a screen.  On a TV resolution
screen, this means that every pixel on the screen can have a different
color, so you have essentially a true-color capability in the system.

We have 2 game controller ports built in.  These game controller ports are
100% compatible with the existing controller ports on the Amiga. They have
been enhanced to extend and support the joypad capability, with the
11-button controller that we support.  One controller is shipped with the
unit and a second can be purchased separately.  In addition, you can
attach the mouse or any other device - joystick - that would normally
operate on the Amiga, that is also electrically compatible, and if the
software supports it, it will operate.  We have attempted to put software
into the system that will accept these other devices, and figure out what
they are, and then try to emulate the joypad capabilities.

We have an auxiliary port on the system.  This auxiliary port is
essentially the Amiga keyboard interface, and as such, the Amiga keyboard
can attach to it.  Our intention with this port was to support other
features, other than keyboards, although keyboards obviously will work.
For example, our intent is that virtual reality-type peripherals can
utilize this port to gain access to the system.  Headsets, handsets, that
type of thing - through this serial port, we have more than enough
performance to control and to operate those types of peripherals.

In addition, the Amiga serial port is also available in this same
connector.  Further, we positioned this connector in a position on the
machine that allows us to add an IR (Infrared) module interface at that
port, if one wished. Most of the game developers which this system was
primarily targeted to don't like to deal with IR because of the
difficulties associated with software, but the machine is capable of being
upgraded to support an IR interface.

Expansion bus - As Jim pointed out, our intention is not to make this a
dead-end machine.  And this is the most important feature, I think, of the
Amiga CD.  It is capable of supporting expansion through the full
availability of approximately a 180-pin connector at the back of the
machine.  The machine also accepts one board inside the unit, therefore
one feature can go inside.  And the architecture is designed such that you
can also extend beyond that single board to further support additional
boards and additional features in the system.

So we have available the full microprocessor bus, very similar to the
situation that we have in the 1200.  We have the full audio bus available
at that interface, and we also have the full video bus available.  A good
example of a peripheral that utilizes most of those capabilities is the
MPEG player that we have been demonstrating here, that supports the MPEG
technology with the compatibility with the new video CD standard which
allows linear play across multiple platforms.

Obviously, other peripherals can be attached to this, and we can make
available to developers information on how to attach peripherals and other
devices to this unit.  We've had a lot of interest in exploring new
opportunities with this device, or as Jim mentioned, it would make a very
interesting TV-top addition, where you could support either satellite or
cable interactivity, plus the ability to play games and play CDs, and
become the ... entertainment center of a home.

Obviously, as you can accelerate other systems, the CPU bus does support
the addition of accelerators.  For example, there's no reason that someone
couldn't design a 25 - 40 MHz 68040, and eventually perhaps, even a 68060,
to add performance to the system.  From the standpoint of being a game
machine, we also want to point out again that it is really an interactive
multimedia player that also supports audio CDs with a graphical user
interface.  Also, it is designed so that the controller - you don't have
to have the TV.  The legends on how to control it as an audio device are
right on the controller board.  So the TV can be off; you don't need the
graphical user interface.  It will play standard audio CDs; it also plays
CD+G; it also supports the Karaoke or Video CD standard - obviously with
the MPEG player module.

It supports a large portion of the CDTV titles. We did an extensive amount
of work to test for compatibility; there are a large number of titles that
are compatible. The major area of difference is the controller area,
versus the CDTV-type controller.  But we went to great effort to take the
top 30 CDTV titles and ensure that they run on the system.  And of course,
we will play all of the new titles that are specifically designed for the
CD32, this meaning, obviously, all the new game software that is under
development.

One of the most important reasons we've been able to garner such
significant software support is the fact that this platform has a very
mature development environment; all of the tools that are available for
the Amiga are available and will operate as a developing environment for
the Amiga CD32.

We have been able to obtain overwhelming developer support in the game
areas.  Initially, we worked very carefully with a small group of
developers, to help us in the definition of the system, and we did
initially limit the number of developers to the set that we could actually
support, and that was very very important to us.  Now, we're in the
position that we can support developers and have a development environment
available, and we're encouraging additional developers.  At this point, we
have in excess of 35 developers that are licensees and are actually
producing titles.  These people didn't sign up just to say they signed up;
they're actually producing titles.  and that's why we're very careful
about the people we've selected; they had to actually produce titles.

We will have over 50 titles by Christmas.  We expect now somewhere around
75 actual titles available.  The software - initially a lot of it is
software that is ported from other Amiga applications.  There are a number
of brand-new applications that are coming out.  Some of them you can see.
For example, Jurassic Park is one of the new applications.   It takes
about 18 months to do a true title, so the really great stuff is a few
months away.  But still, we find that these titles are excellent, and
compared to other competitor's titles, on this platform are outstanding.

Low cost software.  One of the big, major reasons that we've had great
developer support is the fact that the CD technology in itself has a media
that's extremely low cost.  Developers that have been working on these
cartridge type applications, obviously they have to pay a license fee,
they have to pay for the cartridge - as a matter of fact, they actually
have to pay for them in advance - and they have to wait 6 to 8 weeks
before they actually get their product, so inventory management is very
very difficult to do.

Cartridges typically cost somewhere in the order of 10 to 20 dollars,
depending on the amount of ROM involved in it.  In our case, we can have
cost of goods that's less than a dollar.  In the case of cartridges, they
have to be manufactured either by the licenser or by a designated
supplier.  In our case, in our license, you can have them manufactured
anywhere you want.  And the license fee that we charge is $3.00 a disk.
But we only charge it on product that's actually sold. In the case of
cartridges, if you pay the license fee, build 10,000 of them and sell
2,000, you still have to pay for the product.  So it's a much more
flexible environment.  This is what we believe will actively drive the CD
market.  We, for example, are now able to see pricing of CD applications
on this platform that are 50 - 75% less than prices on other platforms. We
think that this is very key to both driving developers, and, of course, a
major benefit to the customers.

I'd like now to spend some time with the other activities that we've had
going on, that we have in other meetings told you about.  Obviously, we
have next-generation capabilities that we're working on, and many of you
have heard of the capabilities of our new triple-A chipset, which when you
compare it to the AGA, we're talking about performance of 10 to 20 times
the capability.

This chipset has actually had a very dramatic in the last week or so; we
actually have running silicon!  I'm pleased to report that we have a lot
of bugs, but we were recently able to bring up software and were able to
show 24-bit true color images, and were able to blit them around the
screen."


That concluded my tape's capacity to absorb Lew's remarks.  However,
thanks to a working pen, I was able to capture these other tidbits:

 - The AAA chipset (4 chips in all) needs a second pass, but Lew expects
fully functional prototypes by next year, and expects AAA to be in
products by mid-year.

 - The A4000T, the tower version of the A4000, is done and was being shown
on the main floor.  Delivery of this product is now in the hands of
Shipping and marketing.

 - Commodore is restarting the manufacture of the A4091 SCSI-II adaptor,
and expects to have the product available in 6 to 8 weeks.

 - The DSP (Digital Signal Processor) project has been suspended.  The
first-pass hardware had been completed, and it was ready to go to gate
array.  Commodore is willing to license this technology to a third party
for free.  (Later, Lew indicated that he'd like to re-start the DSP
project after the first of the year.)  Other products available for
3rd-party license include the AGA Scan Converter (which de-interlaces the
remaining interlaced modes of AGA), the networking software, multiport
serial board, and the Ethernet adaptor.

 - The CD peripheral for the A1200 and A4000 is actively being developed.
 The prototype has been tooled, and Commodore hopes to ship it by the end
of the year.

 - RTG (ReTargetable Graphics) development has been slowed down, but
Commodore expects to complete it and ship it with the AAA chipset.

 - AmigaDOS 3.1, with improved graphics routines and support for the
CD-ROM player, was completed shortly before the show and should be
shipping soon.

 - The A1200 will be equipped with a high density floppy drive.

 - Commodore has no plans for a laptop, but is willing to support a
3rd-party effort, provided they don't create a "deviant" version of the
operating system.

And all too soon, it was over.  Although there were more questions, there
was no more time.  But the "Amiga Rabble" who attended, perhaps fearing
the worst, went away happy.


