                         Same Time, Same Channel
                            by @{" Bill Camarota " link billc }

This month I have decided to talk about scanning camera-ready artwork. By
definition, camera ready art is artwork that has been prepared via the
offset litho process and is devoid of any imperfections whatsoever. It is
the most desirable medium for logo reproduction. Camera-ready art is
always black and white or color separated black and white components of a
color logo. If you have a business and you advertise, make sure to always
request a camera-ready version of your company identity from the printer
and/or artist that you have contracted. This way if you own a scanner, you
will be able to use the artwork to produce your own business related
projects.

On choosing a scanner, I recommend a flatbed scanner. Hand held scanners,
which depend on the steadiness of your hand, yield unpredictable results.
Here at the station I use a Sharp JX100 and an Epson 600C for my freelance
business. The Art Department Professional drivers are used for both
scanners. In my opinion, the ADPro drivers are definitely superior to
others. They have the most versatile settings and produce the most
favorable results.  Now for some useful scanning tips:

1) Always scan artwork and photos at the highest dot per inch setting
possible with your memory configuration. This way, you always have a large
version to reduce to various smaller sizes. The other great advantage to
this method is sharpness. Using a large scan and reducing it produces a
high degree of anti-aliasing.

2) Always scan color in 24bit and black and white work in 8bit gray. This
allows you the option to do bitplane reductions to meet the needs of many
different projects. Save it as a master in which to make all your up and
coming versions.

3) Crop your work. Crop out all unnecessary items. Make your final scan
contain the closest image you desire to be a final product.

4) Scale the screen height of your scans 14%. The reason for this is
aspect ratio. Scanners scan in a square resolution. Two hundred dots per
inch means 200 x 200. Screen displays are in rectangular resolutions, such
as 640 x 400. Reducing the height 14% will correct the image aspect ratio
for rectangular screen resolutions. @{" Example #1 " system "$viewer example1"} shows a logo without height
reduction. Notice the obvious egg shape of the circular component of the
logo. @{" Example #2 " system "$viewer example2"} shows the logo after a 14% height reduction. Now the zero
looks round and circular instead of being stretched.

5) Make sure that you have obtained the rights to reproduce what you scan.
Trademarks and logos should never be used in a project without obtaining
consent.

Here are some addresses and phone numbers to obtain consent to reproduce
major league sports logos:

