                    Mand2000 - Fractals Rediscovered
                            by @{" Sylvia Lutnes " link syl }

                                  Socks

I had become rather blase about Mandelbrot pictures. After a while they
all looked like striped socks descending to a black hole. Then, without
fanfare or hype, along comes Mand2000 to steal my weekend, put a 'no
vacancy' sign on my hard drive, and etch swirling fantasies on my
sleepless eyeballs.

In the first few days I had the program, I saved out almost 8 megs worth
of pictures and not a sock in sight. I've seen things I've never seen
before and been deeper into the set than I would ever have had the
patience for. The palette mapping is superb and gives tremendous variety
since the same rendering mapped different ways is not immediately
recognizable as the same picture. You can get socks if you want...but
you'll probably leave them in the bureau.

Click-click

What you'll notice the most is the interaction. Click-click. You can move
thru the Mandelbrot space with mouse, keyboard, or joystick. Click-click
and zoom in. The screen will be quickly redrawn at the zoomed-to level.
Like draft mode in printing, it's fast, not yet 'pretty' but gives you an
idea of what's there...a preview mode. There is no need to wait so zoom in
some more, click-click. Anytime, anywhere. Want to move to the left? do
so. Mand2000 only redraws what is necessary. Click-click. Oops, went too
far. You can back up. Click-click. Stop, this is a @{" good spot. " system "$viewer Mand"}  Now watch as
the program increases the resolution outward from the center until your
picture is finished.

Do it Amiga Style

Because the program works asynchronously with itself, while you're waiting
for your finished masterpiece you can open another window, click-click to
a new destination and let her rip. Or choose to do the corresponding Julia
in yet another window. Adjust window size, maximum iterations,
color-mapping...and watch the changes in real-time. Open as many windows
as your memory allows..each with its own color-mapping, iterations and
cycle parameters. And there's an ARexx port for each one.

Mand2000 opens in any resolution your Amiga and monitor allows and it also
works happily on Workbench. (AGA machines can brot in 256 colors). You can
set the priority from the program and use shortcut keys for almost all
operations. The Help key and a Status window are available at all times.

Animation

Two types of animations are built in. Morph and Zoom. Zoom creates an
animation from the 'outside' to whatever brot your active window is at.
All you do is select the option from the menu and click on 'Make Movie'.
If you choose not to utilize its built in 'Tween' player mode, you can
select the number of frames, 'Make Movie', then you need to build the anim
file yourself from the completed frames. Morph lets you adjust the shape
of the daddy brot and then morphs between the daddy brot and its
distortion.

Speed

Mand2000 has been optimized for all processors. It will be at least as
fast as the fastest generators around on a 68000. On an 040 it flies.
Because it is so easy to go deep into the set, and because it can
calculate up to 15,000 iterations per pixel, you might want to reduce the
maximum number of iterations when you go too far. However, if you see too
much black in the picture, increase the iterations a bit. The program does
do a very good job of estimating the number of calculations needed at any
level.

No 24-bit, but images can be converted with AdPro, ImageFX, or Brilliance.
It has been reported that some dongles may interfere with zooming so if
there are problems, remove the offending dongle before running. I have
used Mand2000 with the dongles from both Scala and Brilliance without
trouble.

Requirements

Any Amiga running 2.0 or greater.

