                          A TALE OF TWO PRINTERS
                            by @{" David J. R. Ward " link dward}

I was recently looking around for a replacement printer and it came as a
nice surprise to be offered the chance to compare a couple of machines.

Both are bubblejet and are positioned at the lower desktop price range.
The Canon BJ200 has a recommended price of £399, while the Fujitsu B100 is
offered at £349. Both prices exclude VAT. (Editor's Note: VAT is Value
Added Tax, not yet a problem in the U.S.)   Weighing in at six and a half
pounds each, these are no portables and the size and shape of the Canon
does not make for easy transport.

The Fujitsu is just over a foot wide and six inches deep. Its thickness is
also about six inches and this gives it a boxy appearance. In contrast,
the Canon is less deep but has greater height, the front curving up and
back for roughly seven inches. This gives it an avant-garde appearance.
More of a piece of sculpture than a printer. Fujitsu's box reminds me of
those containers you get on the back of lorries.

The B100 has two flaps that unfold to provide paper support and alignment,
one that covers the printhead carriage, another one underneath that
protects the dip switches, and a small one on top that hides a memory card
slot.

The BJ200 has a canyon to its rear into to which a stack of paper is
dropped. This is the auto-sheet feeder that allows you to get on with your
work, rather than have to stand-by with the next sheet. Unfortunately,
such a device is an optional extra on the Fujitsu.

Other such extras include printer emulation cards for Epson and IBM
compatibility, font cards, and expansion memory. The B100 has 8k of RAM on
board, while the BJ200 has 48k. This can be partitioned, according to the
printer driver you are using, as buffer and downloadable font storage.

The Canon supports its own driver or that for the Epson. This is selected
by some of the 12 dip switches under a discrete cover on top of the
printer. Which driver you use also determines how many fonts are
available, graphics quality, and the sizes of the buffer partitions.

On the B100 there are 33 dip switches with a template under the flap for
quick reference on how to set them for paper size, font and so on. The
Fujitsu is driven by the Workbench Preferences HP_Deskjet driver. With the
Canon you can use the Epson LQ driver, or you can apply to Canon for an
Amiga/BJ10 driver.

Although these drivers will work satisfactorily for text, they are no
substitute for custom written software when it comes to graphics. This is
also something that WB1.3 users will have to invest in if they want the
best from either printer, as the drivers of that OS are just not good
enough.

Wolf Faust is a gentleman in Germany who appears to have devoted his life
to writing drivers that work with the Amiga. He is responsible for the
BJ10 driver that Canon supplies free on request, but if you want that
extra bit of quality then you should invest in his CanonStudio.

He has also written a marvellous piece of software to control other
printers, including Lasers and the Hewlett Packard inkjet range. Called
'Studio' it was developed from CanonStudio and has the ability to do
things you only thought possible with more expensive printers (see the May
issue of Amiga Mart for a full review).

It and the Canon specific version are for WB2.0 and 3.0 only. Earlier OS
users will have to upgrade or buy TURBOprint Professional to get anywhere
near these in terms of excellence. Details at the end.

The Canon is back to front, while the Fujitsu is front to back. I am
referring here to the paper path. The auto sheet feeder on the BJ200 makes
life extremely easy. On the B100 you have to load single sheets.

This is done by inserting the page into the slot at the front and pressing
'form feed' so that the drive rollers can grab the paper. The fold down
guide is there to help you align the edge correctly.  If you have
misaligned your sheet by a fraction, this error is exaggerated by the time
the finished page is ejected at the back. Result - lopsided text.

Print speeds are double on the Canon. This is due to its new 16-bit
technology. A page of A4 text takes under 30 seconds, compared to the
B100's minute. In the Fujitsu manual the printer is stated to be a 90
page/hour product. Well, it sounds a lot better put that way.

The difference in text quality from the B100, against the BJ200, is
imperceptible. This shows that you cannot tell 300x300 from 360x360 dpi in
this fashion. This applies to graphics too, but the Fujitsu was let down
by 'banding'.

This effect is caused by misfeeding of the paper during a graphics dump.
It manifests itself as either thin white lines where the printer has moved
the paper a fraction of an inch too much, or as thin black lines where it
the paper has not been moved enough causing 'overstrike'.  In this case I
suffered from white lines, but I think that the problem was exacerbated by
one of the ink nozzles being blocked.

The Fujitsu's Hewlett Packard type cartridge overdoes it with the ink
slightly. The last few lines of text are issued wet whereas on the Canon
no such 'effect' is noticeable. Unless, of course, you immediately run
your finger over it.

Too much ink causes text to 'bleed' on cheap paper, while heavy graphics
dumps make even good paper fell damp. The Canon does not suffer this
problem, outputting dense graphics with ease. Its cartridge managed 700k
characters compared with the Fujitsu's 500k. The Fujitsu is not
recommended for this kind of use.

Both machines accept envelopes, the BJ200 having a height adjustment
levers for both the printhead/paper gap and the sheet feeder.

Comparing the recommended prices of these two machines it would come as no
surprise if I said 'go for the Canon'. The extra £50 gives you an auto
sheet feeder, Epson emulation, and a larger buffer. These same features
added to the Fujitsu B100 would set you back at least another £200,
pushing it into the £500+ bracket - hardly 'low cost' as the Press Release
describes it (actually this is 'low cost' for all those corporate mugs who
use Windows(TM)).

After looking at numerous PC magazines the cheapest I found that the
