                Britain's Revenge?  The Uploads of August
                              by @{" Nick Cook " link nick}

"King George was right," Cosgrove stared morosely into his gin and tonic.
The ice cubes tinkled momentarily against their glass prison. "Bloody
yanks. They only won that war because of the frogs, er, French."

"Let bygones be bygones," responded the Colonel airily. "Well, we can
pretend. After all, the Revolution was over 200 years ago."

"But we'll get our vengeance," Cosgrove muttered into his drink. "Slowly,
in a deliciously devious, dastardly way."

The Colonel examined the end of his cigar as though it was a work of art.
"How, pray tell?"

Cosgrove, his eyes gleaming with an unholy light, leaned over to the
Colonel and whispered. "We'll send the Yanks demos."

The Colonel blanched. "Good God, sir, no! Not that! That's...that's
inhuman!"

"Yes, yes, demos!" Cosgrove sunk back in his leather arm chair. "Those
Amiga-created music videos that push the envelope, as the computer chaps
would say. Animation, music, all blended together!" Cosgrove's grotesque
smile resembled a death's head. "Those creative demos will make them glad
they picked the Amiga as their platform of choice."

He gripped the arms of the chair so tightly his knuckles turned white.
"But here's the best part! Those silly ex-colonists _won't_ be able to run
those bloody things, try as they might!" Veins popped out in Cosgrove's
forehead. A hysterical giggle bubbled forth from his lips. "No! No! Better
yet! _Some_ machines will run the demos, while others won't! Those bloody
yanks will go balmy trying to get them to run! What delicious revenge! Ha,
ha, ha, ha! Those fools, they'll probably think its a conspiracy from the
Trilateral Commission! Ha, ha! No, we'll say they came from Finland!"

Cosgrove's laughter blurred into a high pitched howl, punctuated by gasps
of breath. The other club members glared icily over the tops of their
London Times. The Colonel grabbed the gin and tonic and dashed it in
Cosgrove's face.

"Steady on, man!" The Colonel ordered.

Cosgrove gasped a couple of times and his tense body relaxed. He pulled a
monogrammed handkerchief from his breast pocket and dabbed his face dry.
"Thanks, old chap. I needed that."

"Now no more of the nonsense about demos," the Colonel sat back in his
chair and puffed on his cigar. "Bloody fine idea as it is," he said
quietly. Then he chuckled.

Virtual Dreams (20526 VIRTUALDREAMS242.DMS 597248 bytes) is a forty-five
minute download for the adventurous only. Using DMS is an endeavor in
itself (remember to ignore those "Fatal Error" messages). Postings left in
the HELP! category seems to indicate that some other people have been
successful in getting the demo to run. Alas, not I. My A3000 has a
profound dislike for this demo (or vice versa). By manipulating the
various settings on Degrader, I could control how long it took for my
machine to crash. But I inevitably greeted the guru. On a stock A500, the
demo was reminiscent of a 1960s psychedelic trip colliding with an MRI.

The Steller demo (20488 ASSI_BAN.LHA 34816 bytes) featured an excellent,
professional-looking logo, then the viewer takes an impressive flight
through a custom rotating, zooming fractal. End of Demo on my 3000,
regardless of Degrader's settings. On a plain vanilla 500, the demo
continued on to a dancing mannequin accompanied by a superb Caribbean-
flavored soundtrack. Good stuff.

Chrome's demo (20490 ASSI_CHR.LHA 40960 bytes) worked fine on my 3000,
but, alas, was pretty tame stuff. A graphic, functioning magnifying glass
floats over puzzle motif pictures of credits and greetings. There's also a
plasma cloud that appeared in jigsaw pieces. Not much gut wrenching
excitement here, although those with more of a graphics/programming mind
may find the magnifying glass schtick interesting.

One demo (20489 ASSI_BEY.LHA 27648 bytes) refused to work on my 3000, but
was fine on the 500. The Beyond Force effort focused on some nice morphs,
as well as a dazzling tunnel of light effect.

Crystal's (20617 MELONTETRIS.LHA 35200 bytes) graphics ran on the 3000,
albeit mutely. On the 500, the demo featured dancing geometric shapes, and
a nifty, floating glass ball mirroring Melon's name. The erstwhile
"Russian Theme" bordered on the obnoxious, however.

A solid, driving musical theme matched with ever-changing, soft abstract
images marked Legend's work (20616 LEGEND.LHA 31488 bytes) on the 500.
Crash-o-matic on the 3000.

Compact's intro (20620 SPACEINTRO.LHA 32256 bytes) showed a spacecraft
orbiting a red planet (don't tell NASA), while various greetings scrolled
across the bottom. Dull.

Sco-Pex (20619 SCOOPEX.LHA 22016 bytes) offered a driver's eye view of a
wild ride through a virtual landscape (white columns and triangular green
trees, that sort of thing). I wanted to deposit a quarter to start play.
But not on a 3000.

The demos by Humane (20495 ASSI_HUM.LHA 35456 bytes) and Genocide (20495
ASSI_GEN.LHA 40832 bytes) are all right, if not particularly exciting.
Humane's graphics are interesting dot patterns (this seemed to be all the
rage for this batch of demos), and Genocide's repeated, with different
palettes the same graphic--a man running in a stencil of the group's name-
-while typing out some text. Nice, but nothing to write home about.

Cyberdance (20492 ASSI_CYB.LHA 34688 bytes) featured the most interesting
music of the bunch: it sounded like a snake charmer after too much
caffeine. The graphics consisted of pixelated, spinning skulls, among
others. Unusual demo.

20493 ASSI_EPS.LHA (35072 bytes) is Epsilon's wild, pulsating entry.
Patterns, silhouettes, and images flashed on the screen, accompanied by a
upbeat score. Its almost a disco flashback. Quick, send out for a hot
fudge pizza!

My top pick was Darkness' demo (20528 FIM.LHA 284288 bytes). A spectacular
combination of sight and sound. Fractals, what appears to be retroscoped
animation, flashing text..whoa! In some ways, it resembled a frenetic
version of the James Bond movie credit sequences. This one's worth the
download time (just remember: like all demos, this one may not like
accelerated machines, or 3000s or 4000s; it ran fine on a stock 500). By
the way, rate this one PG for a full-frontal nude lady.

But beware of Cosgrove's warning! Some demos not only require just a
68000, but one with more than one meg of memory. 20621 TSL-AIR.LHA 342912
bytes, 20496 ASSI_NAG.LHA 31232 bytes, and 20527 PARADIGMA.LHA 257536
bytes fall into this realm. PARADIGMA informs you that you're out of
memory; the other two unpack (I assume that from the flashing mouse
arrow), then sit there, doing nothing on a 1 meg 500. When I loaded them
on my 4 meg 3000, these demos loaded, started---and crashed.

ON THE UTILITY FRONT:

Resize (20631 RESIZE.LHA 13952 bytes) is an utility to change the
dimensions of the shell window. The big selling point for Resize is that
its font-sensitive.

What to create screens like the *StarShip*'s opening screen? Try ProANSI
(20576 PROANI114.LHA 56320 bytes). This Shareware program "paints" with
keyboard characters. Finished screens can be in color and can even be
animated. Your artwork is exportable as ASCII, making ProANSI a method to
shoehorn graphics into programs that normally don't support them (e.g.,
text editors, WordPerfect, console devices). Pretty simple to use, as well.

SPYING ON AGNUS, DENISE, GARY...

The Amiga Real Time Monitor (20575 ARTM17.LHA 45824 bytes), by Dietmar
Jansen  &  F.J. Mertens, is for you true Nosey Parkers. The program
displays and, for the technically adventurous and/or adept, controls
various activities in your Amiga. The point and click interface lets you
check out tasks, their priorities, windows, libraries, devices, resources,
memory, and more. ARTM is fully supported by Intuition. It works under
WB1.3 and WB2.x properly, but requires Arp.library 39.+

On the other hand, if you want to make files safe from prying eyes, try
EnC (20641 ENC10.LHA 14464 bytes). Jon Lochner's CLI program encyrpts
files using what is billed as an impossible-to-break coding method.
(Whispering into his pen) "Open Channel D..."

YAKITY, YAK (DON'T TALK BACK!)

YAK (20595 YAK151.LHA 96000 bytes) is not a picture of the hairy goat-like
mammal, rather it is an acronym for "Yet Another Kommodity". Pop this into
your WBStartup drawer and you replace the "standard", separate Commodore
Commodities with a small, all-in-one Commodity which includes: AutoPoint
(activates the window under the pointer), AutoPop (brings the active
window to the front), Cycle screens using the mouse, mouse and screen
blanking, hotkeys, among others goodies. YAK can be highly configured, and
only has differences of opinion with AMOS (although the author Martin
Scott provides a work around). I found the docs, complete as they are, a
little to complicated for their AmigaGuide format; I sometimes got lost.
To be honest, my first reaction to YAK was "eh, so what." But after using
it for a while, I've changed my mind. YAK makes the Workbench a much
easier place to work.

SACREBLEAU! ZE FILE! SHE IZ GONE!

ARestaure (20522 ARESTAURE21.LHA 18304 bytes) undeletes those files you
pushed into magnetic oblivion by accident. It uses a point-and-click
interface (check out the neat way author Jehan-Yves handles English,
French, and German), searches the indicated disk, and restores files to
the RAM: t directory. Shareware: 50 French Francs.



